WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.460
This talk is really themed around data science and macroeconomic data, really though to talk

00:00:06.460 --> 00:00:14.560
about the partnership between Snowflake and Posit, the power of the new native integration

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:16.040
between Posit and Snowflake.

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:19.440
So hopefully we're going to solve a lot of those problems that Mark was just talking

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:20.440
about.

00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:27.400
We're going to look at a quick demo on using external data, internal data, some modeling

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:33.040
in Positron natively in Snowflake, but this is really a very general example of what

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:34.040
we want to do.

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:41.959
Before I kind of kick off into what's going on with Snowflake and Posit, I start every

00:00:41.959 --> 00:00:48.439
talk I give, whether it's a conference talk or a whiteboarding session, just the commercial

00:00:48.439 --> 00:00:54.799
framework around data science that I'm seeing today across the financial services industry.

00:00:54.799 --> 00:00:59.799
I get to talk to a lot of different asset managers, banks, insurance companies, payments

00:00:59.799 --> 00:01:04.519
companies, kind of the whole spectrum of financial services, and this is how we start every single

00:01:04.519 --> 00:01:05.519
talk.

00:01:05.519 --> 00:01:12.239
It's very relevant to the partnership between Snowflake and Posit, and I'll explain why.

00:01:12.239 --> 00:01:15.599
We always start on the right-hand side there, the commercial outcome that we're driving

00:01:15.599 --> 00:01:16.599
towards.

00:01:16.599 --> 00:01:20.279
I think Mark articulated it really well, like why are we doing this?

00:01:20.279 --> 00:01:22.800
Why are we taking on this big data science project?

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:24.000
Why are we doing machine learning?

00:01:24.199 --> 00:01:25.199
Do we need artificial intelligence?

00:01:25.199 --> 00:01:29.480
Then we kind of work backwards to the data state that we need, right?

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:30.480
Is it all structured data?

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:31.919
Is it unstructured data?

00:01:31.919 --> 00:01:32.919
Is it both?

00:01:32.919 --> 00:01:35.879
And then what are kind of the tools that we want to bring to bear to kind of accomplish

00:01:35.879 --> 00:01:36.879
that?

00:01:36.879 --> 00:01:42.360
So I'm going to talk about the partnership, of course, between Posit and Snowflake, but

00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:45.879
even though Mark just mentioned Snowflake quite a few times, which I'm appreciative

00:01:45.879 --> 00:01:50.760
of, I just wanted to mention what Snowflake is, why it's so powerful.

00:01:50.919 --> 00:01:55.680
I'll talk about why it's become so prominent in the world of financial services, but this

00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:59.720
is kind of a complicated snapshot of what Snowflake is.

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:06.040
You can really think of it as a cloud platform with really meaningful separation of storage

00:02:06.040 --> 00:02:07.120
and compute.

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:13.479
So a lot of other platforms now kind of say they have separation of storage and compute.

00:02:13.479 --> 00:02:17.559
If you run your jobs in Snowflake, though, you'll see that there's really no competition

00:02:17.559 --> 00:02:19.639
between resources for those two things.

00:02:19.639 --> 00:02:23.479
So that's why we're the most kind of performant data cloud that's out there right now.

00:02:23.479 --> 00:02:27.559
And then we've added on to that foundation the ability to ingest all sorts of different

00:02:27.559 --> 00:02:31.520
types of data, structured data, unstructured data.

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:35.919
We have a lot of tooling to kind of make visualizations better, make data engineering better.

00:02:35.919 --> 00:02:40.759
But fundamentally what Snowflake is, is it's that platform, that separation of storage

00:02:40.759 --> 00:02:42.600
and compute.

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:46.440
And that becomes really, really important when you want kind of a single source of truth,

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:47.440
right?

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:51.600
You want your data all living in one place, you want your compute all living in one place,

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:55.639
and then with Posit now you can have all your machine learning tools living in that same

00:02:55.639 --> 00:02:56.639
place.

00:02:56.639 --> 00:03:00.199
So one kind of governed architecture for this entire workflow.

00:03:00.199 --> 00:03:06.520
So I want to talk a little bit about why the partnership between Snowflake and Posit is

00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:08.600
super, super powerful.

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:10.080
This is a big reason right here.

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:14.199
So Snowflake, like what do we invest in as a company?

00:03:14.199 --> 00:03:18.080
We invest in the ability to bring more data into Snowflake.

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:22.880
So this is all the kind of different data sources you can stream natively into Snowflake

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:23.880
right now.

00:03:23.880 --> 00:03:28.639
A lot of this goes through something we call Snowflake OpenFlow, but this is where we're

00:03:28.639 --> 00:03:32.479
spending a lot of our native investment dollars right now.

00:03:32.479 --> 00:03:36.600
Not pictured here is a recent acquisition we made of something called Crunchy Data,

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:38.160
a Postgres database.

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:42.440
So we're really, really focused on bringing data gravity into Snowflake.

00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:46.520
So this, you can kind of think of this if you're working at like a big bank, a big

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:52.080
insurance company, this is how your internal data flows into Snowflake.

00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:58.279
So this can be like interactions with customers, internal research reports that you've written.

00:03:58.279 --> 00:04:02.279
If it's an insurance company, you know, insurance companies have people sending them all these

00:04:02.279 --> 00:04:05.679
images of like car accidents and house damage.

00:04:05.679 --> 00:04:10.119
All this data that you have to like ingest into your own environment.

00:04:10.119 --> 00:04:14.160
So Snowflake's doing a ton of investment to make it easy for that data to flow from

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:20.839
whatever its source is coming from into Snowflake in like a governed, secure way.

00:04:20.839 --> 00:04:27.559
On the other side of that, and this is really where things have really exploded for Snowflake,

00:04:27.559 --> 00:04:32.760
is we've built a data gravity just around the financial services ecosystem.

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:35.239
And a lot of this is driven by our marketplace.

00:04:35.239 --> 00:04:38.559
And that will become very relevant to what we're doing with Posit as well.

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:40.359
These are all external sources of data.

00:04:40.359 --> 00:04:44.760
So these are sources of data that insurance companies, asset managers, banks, they don't

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:50.079
produce these themselves, they buy these from other sources, and they consume them via our

00:04:50.079 --> 00:04:51.279
marketplace.

00:04:51.279 --> 00:04:56.480
So we kind of have data flowing in from internal data sources through OpenFlow, and then all

00:04:56.480 --> 00:05:02.160
this external data that's arriving from providers like Bloomberg and Faxhead and Refinitiv,

00:05:02.160 --> 00:05:04.480
all the kind of big market providers.

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:08.399
There's all these little nuanced providers across like the insurance ecosystem, the banking

00:05:08.399 --> 00:05:10.320
ecosystem as well.

00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:14.000
Long story short, this is how the kind of center of data gravity is all moving into

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.600
Snowflake right now.

00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:21.279
Also on that marketplace though is the ability to spin up applications.

00:05:21.279 --> 00:05:25.359
So it's not just a data marketplace, that's how it started many, many years ago.

00:05:25.359 --> 00:05:27.200
It's developed into much more than that though.

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:30.160
So now it's really an applications marketplace as well.

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:34.679
And one of those new applications that you can access on our marketplace is Posit Workbench.

00:05:34.679 --> 00:05:39.640
And I'm going to show you all how it works in real time through my Snow site login in

00:05:39.640 --> 00:05:40.640
just a second.

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:45.359
But you can kind of think of this as like we have an app store that used to be very,

00:05:45.359 --> 00:05:46.760
very data centric.

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:51.920
So a lot of data providers moved on to our app store, you know, LSAG and Bloomberg and

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:53.239
S&P, they were providing data.

00:05:53.239 --> 00:05:57.559
Then we expanded this to include just data applications.

00:05:57.559 --> 00:06:00.920
One of those applications is now Posit, so you can log into Snowflake, you can go to

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:05.279
our marketplace and say I want to pull down data from Bloomberg, data from FactSet, and

00:06:05.279 --> 00:06:09.799
I want to spin up Posit Workbench as well, and now I can be working with that data using

00:06:09.799 --> 00:06:15.239
Posit Workbench all in one governed environment.

00:06:15.239 --> 00:06:18.760
One big question I get is, you know, why is this important?

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:24.079
Why can't I just do this on my desktop if I can just get a really, really beefy desktop?

00:06:24.079 --> 00:06:26.600
Isn't that adequate for what I want to be doing?

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:30.440
I guess if it's beefy enough, yes, like if you have enough RAM, you have enough compute,

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:38.279
you could be, but that kind of second and third line there, robust security and governance,

00:06:38.279 --> 00:06:41.480
from the perspective of a large financial institution, which is really kind of the lens

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:47.320
that I'm coming from, the security and governance can be like the most important thing that

00:06:47.320 --> 00:06:48.320
you're doing.

00:06:48.320 --> 00:06:51.720
So, I mean, I talked about commercial outcomes and how that's super, super important to all

00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:53.760
the work that our data scientists do.

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:59.959
So like when a project is getting spun up, the first call is to the line of business,

00:06:59.959 --> 00:07:00.959
why are we doing this?

00:07:00.959 --> 00:07:02.559
What's the commercial value?

00:07:02.559 --> 00:07:04.679
Second call is always to InfoSec.

00:07:04.679 --> 00:07:06.200
Do we have access to this data?

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:07.200
Can I get this data?

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:08.200
Can I work with this data?

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:13.359
There's a lot of data vendors out there who have very specific clauses that say you cannot

00:07:13.359 --> 00:07:15.839
do X, Y, and Z to this data, right?

00:07:15.839 --> 00:07:18.720
All that governance and security is handled in Snowflake.

00:07:18.720 --> 00:07:23.160
So when you kind of spin up the Posit native app, it inherits all of that governance and

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:29.000
all of that security, right, because you can have the smartest data scientists in the world

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:33.920
who have tons and tons of skills, they need access to the data in order to do their work.

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:39.359
So security and governance, super, super important, and the cool thing is that you inherit all

00:07:39.359 --> 00:07:44.660
of this from your Snowflake policies, right, so that's really, really important.

00:07:44.660 --> 00:07:45.660
How does it work under the hood?

00:07:45.660 --> 00:07:49.720
I'm going to show you guys how it kind of looks to the end user, but I do get this question

00:07:49.720 --> 00:07:51.200
quite frequently.

00:07:51.200 --> 00:07:53.799
How is all of this actually working under the hood?

00:07:53.799 --> 00:07:59.720
So you can see it says Posit and Snowflake full SPCS.

00:07:59.720 --> 00:08:04.440
SPCS is really our container services, Snowpark container services.

00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:10.480
So you can kind of think of this is Posit Workbench, and in private preview, so coming

00:08:10.480 --> 00:08:17.920
very soon, is also Posit Connect, just spinning in a container inside Snowflake, right?

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:21.480
So that's what allows us to kind of push down all of the compute that you're doing with

00:08:21.480 --> 00:08:23.679
that Docker container, right?

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:26.359
So you've spun up a container inside Snowflake.

00:08:26.359 --> 00:08:29.920
It's sitting next to your data, so you get a lot of efficiencies with how you're passing

00:08:29.920 --> 00:08:30.920
data back and forth.

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:34.640
I'll show you guys another cool efficiency that you get with some of the modeling you

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:37.840
can do, but you get that efficiency.

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:42.840
That's also why your security perimeter is never breached, it's never broken.

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:48.719
If you have a security and governance framework set up, you won't get dinged by InfoSec,

00:08:48.719 --> 00:08:53.280
you won't get shut down because you're inheriting everything from your Snowflake infrastructure,

00:08:53.880 --> 00:08:57.679
So you've built your data gravity, you've kind of got your data scientists ready to

00:08:57.679 --> 00:09:01.200
go, now you're giving them access to a tool that sits right next to their data.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:05.239
So it's going to be efficient, it's going to be secure, it's going to be well governed.

00:09:05.239 --> 00:09:09.400
You need all of that, especially if you're at like a big bank, if you want to get any

00:09:09.400 --> 00:09:12.440
value from your data.

00:09:12.440 --> 00:09:15.080
Another question I get is what about my packages, what about my R packages?

00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:19.039
So you can also, I believe coming soon, we're already there, you can use Posit Package Manager.

00:09:19.039 --> 00:09:22.559
It's going to look and feel very similar to how you're doing things on your desktop if

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:23.559
you're used to that.

00:09:23.559 --> 00:09:26.960
It's just when you spin this up, it's going to be running in the Snowflake cloud.

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:30.520
So I'll show you guys what I mean by that right now.

00:09:30.520 --> 00:09:37.400
So I'm going to take you ahead here to the demo portion of this.

00:09:37.400 --> 00:09:43.719
So this is kind of what my research account looks like at Snowflake.

00:09:43.719 --> 00:09:49.520
So this is my data that I have access to, you see I have a database here called Posit

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:50.520
Workbench.

00:09:50.520 --> 00:09:53.960
I have a database called JR underscore DB.

00:09:53.960 --> 00:10:00.640
If I click on this little catalog button here, it has my ability to explore my database,

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:04.320
ability to explore the internal marketplace, which I'll mention at the end of this talk,

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:07.159
and the ability to explore my apps.

00:10:07.159 --> 00:10:10.679
So Posit Workbench is one of the apps that I have in here.

00:10:10.679 --> 00:10:12.679
It's actually the only app that I have in here.

00:10:12.679 --> 00:10:17.799
So once I kind of pull this app off the marketplace, it's now living natively inside of my Snowflake

00:10:17.799 --> 00:10:18.799
account.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.719
So I've already done all the login, so you guys don't have to sit here and watch me kind

00:10:21.719 --> 00:10:24.799
of type in my passwords.

00:10:24.799 --> 00:10:28.280
I'm going to stick to R for what I'm going to show you all here, but you could just as

00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:32.640
easily spin up JupyterLab through Posit Workbench.

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:37.320
Anything you can do on Posit Workbench, you can kind of do natively in Snowflake now.

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:40.919
This is what RStudio Server Pro looks like instead of Snowflake.

00:10:40.919 --> 00:10:44.679
Just to kind of highlight what's going on here, I'm not going to do any work in this,

00:10:44.679 --> 00:10:46.840
I just want to show you all what's going on here.

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:51.559
You can see that this looks and feels kind of like your desktop instantiation of this

00:10:51.559 --> 00:10:55.559
or what you might be used to spinning on an EC2 instance, but instead it's running on

00:10:55.559 --> 00:10:57.119
Snowflake Compute.

00:10:57.119 --> 00:11:01.119
So any work that we run here, any R code that we run, it's just going to get pushed down

00:11:01.119 --> 00:11:06.000
into Snowflake and it's going to kind of have easy access to your data back and forth.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:13.840
So this is the RStudio version of this, but I wanted to show you guys what the Positron

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:17.440
version looks like, because I found some really cool things around Positron.

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:22.479
So first of all, Positron is the new IDE, I think there's been a lot of talks about

00:11:22.479 --> 00:11:26.559
it here, so I won't belabor what's going on here.

00:11:26.559 --> 00:11:29.119
This is what Positron looks like inside of Snowflake.

00:11:29.119 --> 00:11:34.880
So same thing, I'm kind of doing everything inside of my Snowflake computing environment.

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:40.200
Since Positron is built off of VS Code, you also get to take advantage of all the VS Code

00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:42.000
tooling that we've built at Snowflake.

