on this.

00:13:06.419 --> 00:13:15.739
I get to take advantage, of course, of all of R's visualization, so I get to use ggplot

00:13:15.739 --> 00:13:18.099
for all my plots.

00:13:18.099 --> 00:13:21.859
Almost everyone I know still uses ggplot for all their visualizations, so we've always

00:13:21.859 --> 00:13:24.739
wanted to be able to run this natively in Snowflake.

00:13:24.739 --> 00:13:27.919
So that's kind of some light wrangling.

00:13:27.919 --> 00:13:33.299
From here, we can add some scale, some lag, some rolling features, and then what I'm going

00:13:33.299 --> 00:13:37.419
to do is I'm going to join this up with other data that I have in Snowflake, this loan data

00:13:37.419 --> 00:13:38.619
here.

00:13:38.619 --> 00:13:46.539
So this is from a Kaggle competition on, I guess, some credit data, you could say.

00:13:46.539 --> 00:13:50.859
I'm going to kind of marry that up with some of that macro data, do some light wrangling

00:13:50.859 --> 00:13:57.020
to it, do some visualizations, but what's really, really neat here, and there's a whole

00:13:57.020 --> 00:14:02.539
blog post on this that came out long ago, is now I'm going to kind of pass that data

00:14:02.539 --> 00:14:08.140
that I've joined up to recipes via tidy models.

00:14:08.140 --> 00:14:11.340
So I'm going to use recipes for some feature engineering, and then we're going to fit a

00:14:11.340 --> 00:14:14.539
model to this, a linear regression model.

00:14:14.539 --> 00:14:16.820
So nothing too fancy there.

00:14:16.820 --> 00:14:21.119
The really, really cool thing is that once we do all of this, we can use an R package

00:14:21.119 --> 00:14:26.020
called orbital to turn this into a Snowflake object, and that's going to let us take that

00:14:26.020 --> 00:14:30.460
model that we just fit and basically store it up in Snowflake and then take advantage

00:14:30.460 --> 00:14:35.219
of the Snowflake compute engine if we want to do inference or prediction on that model.

00:14:35.219 --> 00:14:36.820
So super, super powerful.

00:14:36.820 --> 00:14:42.520
Again, you're doing all your work in R, everything in our studio or Positron as you're used to.

00:14:42.520 --> 00:14:46.419
You can use the entire tidy models framework, including recipes, and you can kind of push

00:14:46.419 --> 00:14:49.820
it back to Snowflake for production work.

